      "type": "add",
      "id": "8f5a735764dc1e12",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "8f5a735764dc1e12",
        "text": "At the level of autopoiesis, the system confines itself to the reproduction of its operations. The differentiation of system and environment requires an observer to link the internal processes with the outside world [→[[Operation/Observation]]]. Thus, only the observer can attest to the existence of causal relationships between environment and system. Everything that can be said about an autopoietic system — including ideas of time, function, adaptation, evolution — is voiced by an observer and does not concern the workings of the operations. At a certain level of complexity, the system itself can be the observer of its own autopoiesis."
      },
